text: You can gleam a fair bit from the style of a trailer, and this is very disappointing.  The reason the books are so enthralling is down to the way they weave the tale with these incredible characters and a world that defies expectation. You can tell the studio have just tried to boil it down to an action flick about portals, rather than the slow cooking epic that it should be.  There's no sense of purpose, no build up of mystery, no silence, no beauty.   The Logan trailer was more artistic than this. This feels almost like Resident Evil.  It's a real shame. I wish they had more guts to actually produce something meaningful.

text: I was excited for this, being a huge fan of the series. But sadly this looks like it's going to be a generic Hollywood action blockbuster. The Dark Tower is so so so much more than that. It's an epic story, and when I say epic I mean EPIC. It's got action yes, but it's also got deep meanings, complicated relationships, and love stories that expand different times and dimensions, that when you finish, it makes you question reality and existence. It should really be adapted as an epic HBO show, ala Game of Thrones, in order to explore all the characters' rich history and journeys that can't be done in one movie. Also where is Eddie Dean, Susanah and Oy - who make up the rest of Roland's Ka-tet? It's like doing Lord of the Rings, but with only Gandalf and Frodo. I hope I'm wrong, I really want this to be good but the trailer doesn't feel me with confidence.

text: There's no way they can pull it off. The Dark Tower series had too much details, twist and turns to be confined into a film. There's no way they can do enough character development or have enough screen time, even if they made the movie over 8 hrs, to do the books justice. The Dark Tower series is one of the toughest reads in horror/fantasy. Specially since Steven king tied all his works to the Dark Tower. Books are confusing enough for most I don't see how they can dumb it down for the average movie goer while maintaining the awesomeness of the books. IMO they can probably make a trilogy out of each book and still have a hard time telling the story. From the trailer it looks like they change everything except Ronald's name and that he's a gunslinger.

text: Looks cool...but not really anything like I'd imagined with regard to how it connects to the books. Yes it's a continuation of them - in a sense - and not a re-telling of the originals but I worry it lacks the substance of what was so exciting about the books (the magic, mysticism, history and just general depth). Ok fine, they have to adapt it to suit general audiences but 1 of 2 things concern me; 1) they haven't put enough substance in the film to set it aside from other mainstream action-adventure films (and makes it a bit bland) or 2) they try and cram way too much into the film and confuse the audience (ones who haven't read the books and can't follow the story), of which options I can't say which I'm mostly worried about. If they plan to do a number of sequels to expand on it all, then great. With all that being said, I'll reserve judgement until I see the film; Idris and Matthew are both fantastic actors and I am genuinely curious about the whole continuation and imagining of Roland's journey; hopefully it won't disappoint.

text: I'm a huge fan of the books. This is about as far removed from what was in the books as I ever could have imagined. Roland should be a tortured but magnetic individual. Elba's performance just makes him look brooding. The Man in Black should be terrifying, menacing, and mysterious. Here he just isn't. Jake should be entirely different. Even modern NYC clashes with the feel of NYC in the books. The Tower looks like something out of the Hobbit--with its beams looking like CG blobs.  The worst part is the Matrix-esque choreography or the fight sequence (which ultimately NEVER happens in the books). In the books the gunslinging was gritty and dirty and grounded in some sort of reality. Here he's literally THROWING BULLETS and CATCHING THEM WITH HIS GUN. WHAT?  The first book in the series depicts the world as a wasteland. Here it looks lush and overgrown. Yes, later in the series you see forest, but the world is an irradiated dump with terrifying mechanical bears w/ satellite dishes on their heads. I see nothing that resembles the setting of the books here.  I know that people will immediately start calling people racist for mentioning how Idris Elba was miscast, but it really has nothing to do with the color of his skin. They should have just cast an unknown and used Clint Eastwood from Unforgiven as a starting point because what I'm seeing in this trailer is not the Roland that I fell in love with.

text: My concern with this trailer is not the actor playing Roland Deschain is black (Seriously who gives three fucks?) but rather that they appear to have abandoned the addicted nature of the character I so loved. The fact that Jake would need to sit him down and explain the tower will help save his world, one that is full of life to ROLAND? Fuck that, Roland would walk right over jake's corpse to get to his goddamn tower and it wouldn't matter if Jake's world was long dead or brimming with life. He was an addict. A knight with a quest for the holy grail who forgot the reason the grail was supposed to be important in the first place and then, along the way remembered it piece by piece. It was an evolution of watching an animal who was once a man become human once more and that's what I loved. This puts him out to be something of a lame ass super hero with little to no depth save "be a badass".  I'm really hoping they didn't change the fact that Roland killed Jake. I really really hope that is in the flick and they do it justice.

text: Ahh, so it's not The Dark Tower. It's a smoothed off, lowbrow, gun-fu, action blockbuster attaching some of the same character names to a speck of the original plot. I'm sure that a lot of people who haven't read the book will like it.  It's such a shame because the books are so darn cinematic already. I never expected a movie to tackle the books 100% faithfully (how could it?) but it seems that the grit and pathos of the original has been entirely ignored, shirked even. I'd rather see Roland stagger messily through the incident at Tull, bloody, stabbed in several places, forced to murder an entire town, than see him drop-load his six shooters, kill a baddie, then say a one-liner... Maybe I'm just being a bumhug. Hopefully one day some brave group of souls will get the chance to tackle this appropriately, perhaps as a series, each season representing one of the books. It's a shame really, Matthew McConaughey would have made a fantastic Man in Black in a proper version of the tale.   Oy!

text: For those of you who have not read "The Dark Tower" series, Roland of Gilead (the gunslinger) is like a Jedi knight in the old west, who uses pistols instead of light sabers. He is absolutely one badass mammy-jammy, period. Some of the things he does in the novel-series are mind boggling awesome.  I've read 95% of all Stephen King novels. "The Dark Tower" series is, by far, his very best work. At least six of those seven series novels I literally couldn't put down, and I read them within a few days. "The Dark Tower" overlaps into A LOT of his other works, mainly The Stand ("the walking dude" is¬†a bad guy in The Dark Tower also), Salem's Lot, and many, many others. SK did a superb job in The Dark Tower of mixing all these other books into TDT, in a way that makes sense.  Having said that, it's difficult to watch this trailer without a critical eye. What I mean is, there are significant differences in TDT novels, and several things I've seen in this trailer. Still, it looks like it will be a good movie (definitely), but as an avid admirer of TDT novels, and as always happens when I read a novel first, and then watch the Hollywood adapted movie afterward, I know I'll¬†be disappointed in the end and as always happens, I'll wonder why in the hell Hollywood didn't just simply follow the novel's structure and be done with it??  Bottom line, I'll definitely go see it. One tiny detail is (for example), it looks like the movie is going to bypass the numerous, single doors standing up on a beach...each one opening into a different world and on the beach are these freaked out shellfish called "lobstrosities" (just one example).  Anyway,¬†that lingering disappointment will be watching it with me.

text: "There are other worlds than this": For all of the haters (before the movie is even released!) please consider this when watching movie adaptations of Stephen King's books. He's already written the books; he's told "his" side of the story, so when he signs over movie rights he's allowing another creative entity to take from his work and tell the story from "their" point of view. If he's OK with it, so am I. And once I've seen the "new" point of view, it's then and only then, that I can judge it on its own merits or failings. Either way, I still have SK's masterpieces on my bookshelves to visit again and again, like dear old friends.

text: This will come full circle, so continue to read: I went to a local Chinese restaurant and ordered their sesame chicken.  It was good.  When I went back for seconds I asked the staff for extra sesame seeds because my last order had none.  They told me they don't put sesame seeds in because some people might be allergic.  I then asked, "But you put sesame oil in, don't you?"  They answered, "No." for the same reason.  Again, it was a good dish.  But for God's sake,  "HOW CAN YOU CALL IT SESAME CHICKEN WHEN THERE IS NO SESAME???"  Idris Elba? Great actor.  Phenomenal actor.  The Dark Tower? An AMAZING EPIC STORY!!!  When The Shawshank Redemption made the screen, the character portrayed by Morgan Freeman in the book was a white guy.  An Irish guy, actually.  That is why his nickname was Red.  The race change had no effect on the story or the context.  However, in The Dark Tower, it is EXTREMELY relevant.  I see they forced it to fit by simply omitting main characters and chopping out a third of the story to accommodate the change.  Does anyone else recall that the actors were announced about two weeks after the national upset regarding "not enough African Americans winning Oscar's or having lead roles"? Coincidence?  I don't think so.  :(   Everything said and done, this might be a great movie in it's own way, but don't call it The Dark Tower the same as my dinner was NOT Sesame Chicken!!!!

text: Okay, I'm kinda more looking forward to this after reading hints that this might be a sort-of sequel to the Books instead of a straight adaptation (which I'm actually fine with, since I was never able to figure out how anyone adapting them into a film would deal with the whole 'Stephen King himself is an important bit player in the last book'-Plotpoint).  BUT visually, this really doesnt look like how I have imagined TDT to be like. I was always thinking of a gritty cross between Sergio Leones' westerns and Horror-Movies, of these films having some kind of road-movie Feel (the very sparse and dark fist book in particular, which (right now) make me think of a mixture between "Valhalla Rising" and "Logan"), with the portions taking place in "our" world and the large backstory-portion in the fourth novel offering some notable contrast in terms of style and feel.  This, however, just looks... generic. Been there, done that.

text: when I heard that Idris Elba would be in this I knew he'd be headlining the movie as Roland (been years since I read the book can't remember outright, but I'm sure neither him nor his dad were black. the illustrations that accompanied the books after wizard and glass certainly didn't help portray him this way. Back when this movie was all speculation and rumors back in the day I heard they were going to cast Havier Bardem which while he doesn't have the pull that Idris does today it was pretty close to the image I had of Roland in my head ).  When I heard Mccaunaghey was in it I thought he was going to play Eddie (Although he may be getting on in years for that role, he might suit Randall Flag better.). Dunno about the boy, but I'm sure any child actor can play Jake. What really miffed me about the advert is it seems like not only is it going to be a bit of a departure from the opening act of the dark tower series, but the editing the action sequences and the music just makes it seem like it's going to be another brainless action flick that'll be on par with the cringy likes of this years King Arthur. I hope they prove me wrong, I've been waiting fifteen years for this to find it's way on the big screen, and I'm sure a lot of people have been waiting twice as long as I have.

text: In the original story the Man in Black was simply a catalyst for the plot arc. A temporal, transitive relationship between Roland and the Dark Tower. The Dark Tower was the physical manifestation and allegory for Roland's purpose and greater purpose, and more importantly an absolution for the meaning of all things. It's the deepest relatable purpose and enigma of man. The book produced a quasilinear story line that attempted to slowly unravel this meaning, with the omega being the Dark Tower. So, from the trailer, that plot has been diluted into the Dark Tower being a secondary plot device that need's to be saved. Why should I care?

text: A couple of issues. First, Idris Elba is way too buff to be the Gunslinger. Idris looks like a marine and he is good looking. In the books, Roland was often referred to as "long, tall and ugly". I always pictured Clint Eastwood...lanky, but not overly intimidating looking. Skilled, not physically imposing. Casting Matthew McConaughey as the man in black is another curious choice. He's too cool...he's like George Clooney.  I would have gone with Javier Bardem for Roland...have him drop 20 lbs for the role. Bardem looks like an addict and that's what Roland truly is. Brad Dourif would have been my choice for the man in black...he played Grima Worm Tongue in the Lord of the Rings. The Man in Black is a liar and a scoundrel...a super natural weasel. Brad Dourif could be that guy. In the end, Hollywood is twisting the story into a perceived market. It's what they usually do. Money over art. I get it, but it'd have been better if some independent studio got to do this film.

text: Before I start¬†this comment I want to state that I am mixed race, so¬†is my wife, and so¬†are our children. So I am the last person who could be accused of being "racist". My concern here is, was Idris Alba the right PERSON to play Roland. He is a fine UK actor and was outstanding in Luthor, loved his performance. But is Roland¬†black here for the sake of it? With¬†the "PC" thing of making a character "non white" or "no longer white", we have¬†had rumours of Mr Elba set to play James Bond and Dr Who. Making the character black for the sake of it. Why not make him Chinese, Indian, or an Eskimo? Is Roland white in the books? The gunslingers in those towns, in the World Moved On, based on Wild West towns would have all been white Americans. Susannah/Detta/Odetta was black, and is stated as so. ¬†¬†Roland, Eddie and Jake are white. Mr Elba as Roland in this post apocalyptic world has a big dose of Denzel Washington as Eli about him. There are many actors who could have portrayed this role more like the book. Not quite a Clint Eastwood way, but closer to that kind of world. In a way this "let's make the character black", "let's have a¬† white character played by a black actor" is¬†the most offensive things of all. Offensive to blacks and white. Offensive to Chinese and Indians. And probably offensive to the¬†Eskimos¬†as well. Hell,¬†if James Bond, originally taken to be a white Englishman, then¬†altered to be half Scottish/half Swiss, why couldn't he be descended from Greenland inuits? Makes as much sense as¬†making his ancestors from Africa.

text: This movie is an affront to the Dark Tower series.  There are SEVEN full length novel to the Dark Tower. Hollywood made a movie out of each of the Lord of the rings books, the took the Hobbit, which is HALF the length of the other books and made three movies out of it. This is Stephen King's opus, and they want to make ONE 1:35 movie out of it?  As the director and producer I would be ashamed.  They have probably never even read the books. To be done right, a movie from the first two books, then a movie from the next three, then a final movie from the last two. This would be the minimum number, simply out of respect for the series.  So many of Stephan King' books tie into this series: Hearts of Atlantis, Salem's Lot just to name a couple. So Hollywood Producers, directors and writers, read the books FIRST, then make the movie.  I am SO tired of the "Poetic licence" taken by Hollywood now-a-days. Either make the movies true to the books, or don't make them at all. If I have offended Hollywood, then good, I do not apologize for it.  You have been making sequels for so long that a great original comes along and you have no idea how to treat it.  Shame on all of you.
